'''Scientific lacuna''' describes an area of science that has not been studied but has the potential to be studied scientifically.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Routledge Handbook of Translation Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s-SnQWJLO4EC|website=Google books|accessdate=1 January 2015|date=2013|isbn=9781136242144|page=431}}</ref> Often, this may be the case because it falls between different areas of sciences, such that it doesn't fall into a single specific [[discipline]] of science.<ref>{{cite book|title=Lewis and Clark: Pioneering Naturalists|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dWbS4RHIXp8C|website=Google books|accessdate=1 January 2015|date=2003|isbn=9780803264342}}</ref> However, it also may be the case that the right situation for study has not yet occurred, or the conditions for study have been too [[ephemeral]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Studies on the Structure of Time: From Physics to Psycho(patho)logy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LMsDqsvcxckC|website=Google books|accessdate=1 January 2015|date=2000|isbn=9780306464393|page=258}}</ref> Scientific lacunae often have the potential to be studied in the future when more areas of sciences are explicitly defined or the right conditions do occur, yet this can be made difficult if the area of science is commonly not considered a proper area for [[Scientific method|scientific study]].<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Journal of the American Medical Association|title=American Medical Association|volume=35|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tqUhAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=1 January 2015|date=1900|issue= |publisher=American Medical Association.|issn=0002-9955|page=202|doi=10.1001/jama.1900.24610040009001b}}</ref>

